    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Use the determinant method to find the inverse of the
following matrices</p><p>\[A = {@A@},\] \[B = {@B@}.\]</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li><div>\(A^{-1} = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</div></li>
<li><div>\(B^{-1} = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</div></li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>To find the inverse of \(A = {@A@}\) using the determinant method will require four steps.</p>
<p>First we find the determinant of \(A\).</p>
<p>\[ \det(A) = {@detA@}. \]</p>
<p>Since \(\det(A) \neq 0\) the inverse of \(A\) exists.</p>
<p>Now, we replace each element of \(A\) by its cofactor.</p>
<p>The cofactor of \({A}_{ij}\) is the determinant of the matrix that remains when row \(i\) and column \(j\) are
    removed, multiplied by \((-1)^{i+j}\). So we have,</p>
<p>{@cofactorsA@}.</p>
<p>Then we transpose the result to obtain the adjoint matrix:</p>
<p>\(\mathrm{adj}(A) = {@cofactorsA@}^{T} = {@adjA@}\).</p>
<p>Finally we obtain \(A^{-1}\) using the following formula:</p>
<p>\(A^{-1} = \frac{1}{\det(A)} \mathrm{adj}(A) = \frac{1}{@detA@} {@adjA@} = {@ta1@}\).</p>
<p>The method can be used to determine \(B^{-1}\) similarly, which gives \( B^{-1} = {@ta2@}.\)</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
